      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_001_7",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "A–3 The limit is 0; we will show this by checking that dn = 0 for all n ≥ 3. Starting from the given matrix, add the third column to the first column; this does not change the determinant. However, thanks to the identity c   , gat the form",
        "bbox": [
          0.5231372549019608,
          0.16484848484848486,
          0.9192156862745098,
          0.2515151515151515
        ],
        "order": 3
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_001_2",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "A–1 Yes, it does follow. Let P be any point in the plane. Let ABCD be any square with center P. Let E, F, G, H be the midpoints of the segments AB, BC, CD, DA, respec- tively. The function f must satisfy the equations",
        "bbox": [
          0.09333333333333334,
          0.16545454545454547,
          0.49019607843137253,
          0.22363636363636363
        ],
        "order": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_001_11",
        "observed_type": "list",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "with the first column being a multiple of the second. Hence dn = 0.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5576470588235294,
          0.3406060606060606,
          0.9184313725490196,
          0.3696969696969697
        ],
        "order": 5
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_001_3",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "If we add the last four equations, then subtract the first equation and twice the second equation, we obtain 0 = 4f (P), whence f (P) = 0.",
        "bbox": [
          0.12627450980392158,
          0.35393939393939394,
          0.49019607843137253,
          0.3975757575757576
        ],
        "order": 6
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_001_12",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Remark. Another way to draw the same conclu- sion is to observe that the given matrix is the sum of the two rank 1 matrices Ajk = cos(j − 1)ncosk and B jk = − sin(j − 1)n sink, and so has rank at most 2. One can also use h matrices Aj = ei(i−1)k), e−i(j−1)n+k.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5552941176470588,
          0.37454545454545457,
          0.9192156862745098,
          0.46484848484848484
        ],
        "order": 7
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_001_4",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Remark. Problem 1 of the 1996 Romanian IMO team selection exam asks the same question with squares re- placed by regular polygons of any (fixed) number of vertices.",
        "bbox": [
          0.12705882352941175,
          0.4018181818181818,
          0.49019607843137253,
          0.46
        ],
        "order": 8
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_001_5",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "A−2 Multiplying the first differential equation by gh, the sec- ond by f h, and the third by fg, and summing gives",
        "bbox": [
          0.09333333333333334,
          0.4703030303030303,
          0.4894117647058824,
          0.5
        ],
        "order": 9
      }
    ]
